commit_message:
Add API integration tests (#7561)

* Copied Dockerfile from https://github.com/Graylog2/graylog-docker

* Copied graylog.conf and log4j2.xml from https://github.com/Graylog2/graylog-docker

* Add MongoDB

* Add ElasticSearch

* Fix ElasticsearchInstance so that existing IT still work

* Start containers in parallel to reduce startup time

Startup time is now limited by the time it takes the server container to start. That can be optimized later.

* Moved container instances into GraylogBackend

This leads to a clean separation between managing containers (GraylogBackend)
and junit integration (GraylogBackendExtension).

* Use real artifacts instead of relying on manually created ones

- Take server jar from target folder
- Take sigar lib from lib folder

* Load default plugins

The definition of plugin jars in api-it-tests.properties is a bit verbose,
but I decided to leave it like this, because I think it's easier to understand
than dynamic generation of jar file locations in code.
We might still decide to make it more dynamic when enabling additional plugins.

* Fix forbiddenapis errors

* Set permissions for docker-entrypoint.sh explicitly

Local filesystem permissions don't seem to be retained reliably

* Fix dumb mistake in NodeInstance#getApiAddress

* Use URI instead of filename

...because forbiddenapis says so.

* Mvn package server when executing tests from Intellij

* Move new integration tests to existing module

- Moved the test class
- Deactivated all old tests
- Changed how docker-entrypoint.sh resource is converted to file
  Before it went via URI, which doesn't work when executing tests
  from a different module. Write resource to temp file instead,

* Add explanatory comments for permissions workarounds

* Mount jars into container instead of building into image

* Move full backend test to separate module

- Created new module full-backend-tests
- Run all tests in module with failsafe, not surefire,
  to ensure that they only run on `mvn verify`.
  This allows running `mvn package` without running
  these slow tests.

* Run only mvn package on travis

Travis doesn't package plugins, so extra steps would  be needed to
run full backend tests.
It should be sufficient to run these tests only in the jenkins build

* Disable failsafe integration tests on travis explicitly

`-Dmaven.test.skip=true` was not enough in the second `after_success` step.

* Add CLASS and METHOD lifecycle for backend

- Added serverLifecycle property to ApiIntegrationTest annotation
- default to METHOD where server is restarted after each test

* Avoid recreating containers for GraylogBackend per test class

Converted GraylogBackend to singleton. This ensures that images
and containers can reused globally.

* Add license headers

* Use project graylog.conf instead of copy

* Use project log4j2.xml instead of copy

* Package jars when not running in Maven

...instead of when running in Intellij explicitly

* Extract tmp file creation from NodeInstance

- Added separate class ResourceUtil to extract this
  detail from NodeInstance

* Allow setting env var to skip packaging

- Use existing jars, if env var GRAYLOG_IT_SKIP_PACKAGING
  is set to "true" (ignoring case)

* Upgrade rest-assured to 4.2.0

* Allow remote debugging of graylog server

This allows to attach a remote debugger to the server container.
The biggest caveat is that the dynamic port to which the debugger can be
attached is only known after starting the container. Hence one would
have to set a breakpoint after the container start to pause execution,
identify the debug port and start the remote debugger with it.

- Added debug toggle via env var GRAYLOG_IT_DEBUG_SERVER
- Added optional debug build arg to container
- Added logging of debug port, if debugging is enabled
- Extracted building the container to NodeContainerFactory

* Add license headers

* Disable purging data for Lifecycle.CLASS

Doesn't work, because you can't wipe the mongodb from underneath a running server.
Tests failed, because all permissions were gone. But there would probably have been
even more issues like that.
So when Lifecycle.CLASS is chosen, all data remains in the DBs across tests.

* Enable Elasticsearch fixtures

* Refactored BackendStartupIT#importsElasticsearchFixtures

... to make it easier to understand

* Cleanup

* Added param object NodeContainerConfig

* Added README explaining local config options

Placed it in the `testing.completebackend` package in lack of a better
idea where to put it. Can be moved somewhere else after the contents
have been reviewed.

* Reduce docker-entrypoint.sh to necessary parts

- Deleted unnecessary code from docker-entrypoint.sh
  (was originally copied from https://github.com/Graylog2/graylog-docker)
- Created contentpacks dir also in Dockerfile
  Dir creation was actually redundant in Dockerfile and docker-entrypoint.sh.
  The contentpacks dur was the only one missing in Dockerfile.

* Skip forbiddenapis check in MavenPackager

* Add braces around one-line conditional blocks

...to comply with coding standards.

* Start mongodb and node in sequence

...because starting them in parallel is not safe, as @bernd
pointed out in a review.

* Move configuration of RequestSpecification to GraylogBackendExtension

- Make RestAssured RequestSpecification injectable to allow reuse
- Configure baseUri, port, and basePath to avoid having to concat
  the api path in every test

* Set additional env vars in NodeContainerFactory

- GRAYLOG_LB_RECOGNITION_PERIOD_SECONDS: save time on server shutdown
- GRAYLOG_VERSIONCHECKS: avoid contacting version check service
- add explanatory comment for ADMIN_PW_SHA2

* Use constant for GRAYLOG_HTTP_BIND_ADDRESS

* Add JavaDocs to explain the ApiIntegrationTest annotation

* Log Maven command when packaging fails

* Improve temp file creation

- More descriptive filename
- Use `File.createTempFile` explicitly
- Delete on exit

* Reset skip flag for old integration tests to "true"

Setting it to "false" slipped in when investigating how difficult it would
be to port them to the new solution.

* Use explicit Locale for String.format

...as required by our forbiddenapis check

* Add check for Maven executable

During his review @kmerz had the issue that the Maven executable
couldn't be found and the resulting error message was not very
helpful for him.
This should make that error more explicit for the user.

* Fix maven command

Accidentally left in "echo $PATH" after debugging. :/

* Added alternative check for failing maven command

...to see which one triggers on @kmerz's system.
Will remove one of them afterwards.

commit_message:
CDPD-12840 Relocate Jersey packages in schemaregistry-client in order to avoid conflict with other components.

Jersey is relying on jaxws-rs for sending REST requests. Unfortunately it is possible for other, external components to also use jaxws-rs, but a different version. If the two versions are on the same classpath then we see conflicts. In order to avoid conflicts, we have relocated the packages used by schemaregistry-client, so the package javax.ws.rs becomes com.hortonworks.registries.shaded.javax.ws.rs. This way, both jaxws-rs libraries are on the classpath, but due to the difference in package names they are not in conflict.

Set version to 0.9.1 in order to avoid conflicts with the snapshot repo.

Change-Id: I4053423c4c6163ce3d3bd8080c27bd529f98d88e
possible_reason: CDPD-12840 Relocate Jersey packages in schemaregistry-client in order to avoid conflict with other components.

commit_message:
IOT-32 IOT – Make Logging Frameworks Coherent Across Libraries and IOT Codebase

* IoTaS codebase, Apache Storm, Dropwizard relies on slf4j
  * which means we can select underlying logging framework
* But Dropwizard is tightly coupled with logback
  * Main entry for IoTaS is 'webservice', which relies on Dropwizard
* Choosing 'logback' as underlying logging framework would be fine
  * Apache Storm itself has log4j2 as underlying logging framework
  * so exclude logback-classic from 'storm' module
possible_reason:
* IoTaS codebase, Apache Storm, Dropwizard relies on slf4j
* which means we can select underlying logging framework

commit_message:
Upgrade base pom 15.3 -> 15.7

This change was necessary to get the required jersey server version to
work with the most recent AWS SDK. However, it required a handful of
internal changes to get it to behave properly. Most importantly, these were
- Major version bump from jersey 1 to jersey 2, which included migrating
  between groupId's. It only required one piece of code-rewriting, which
  was reasonably small.
- Migrating groupId's from com.codahale.metrics to io.dropwizard.metrics.
  There was no real code changes involved, but Maven couldn't detect
  artifact conflicts between these two because they had different
  groupId's even though they were the same artifact. This meant that
  the dependency resolution had to be done by hand, so I just
  migrated to the newer version.

commit_message:
TINDER-72: Update JID cache implementation

This replaces ConcurrentLinkedHashMap with Caffeine in this project (which applies to caching in the JID class).

Small behavioral changes were introduced:
- The caches are now byte-size limited (as opposed to element-size).
- caches are now exposed, for others to (re)configure them (OF-1799).
- API change: an exception that was never throwns was removed from the signature of JID methods.
- An optimization was removed, where a computation could add more than one value to a cache.

commit_message:
Mongo Adapter. Replace Fongo by Mongo Java Server (embedded mongo for tests)

Traditionally we have used [Fongo](https://github.com/fakemongo/fongo) as our fake mongo server. Unfortunately,
development on that project has staled and it is not compatible with latest mongo driver versions (3.6+).

[Mongo Java Server](https://github.com/bwaldvogel/mongo-java-server) is more active and passed all integration tests.

Closes #929

commit_message:
Upgrade mongo java driver 3.12.2 -> 4.1.1

Larger effort than expected since it has a few incompatible
changes with 3.x version.

Drop old reactive module `mongodb-driver-reactivestreams` dependency since
it is already included with 4.x

Adjust generated BSON queries for `$and` / `$not` cases.
Some changes in `Filters` class (eg. [JAVA-3338](https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/JAVA-3338) caused exact query checks to fail.

Add explicit negation simplification for `IS_PRESENT` / `IS_ABSENT` and
`IS_EMPTY` / `NOT_EMPTY` operators.

Fix Jackson / Gson and BSON CodecRegistry adapters after [JAVA-3506](https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/JAVA-3506).

Closes #1242
possible_reason: Upgrade mongo java driver 3.12.2  laifuhewb  4.1.1

commit_message:
Upgrade TinkerPop to 3.5.0 [tp-tests]

1. Bump TinkerPop dependency from 3.4.10 to 3.5.0 and resolve
dependency conflicts. Several jackson packages are ignored from
requireUpperBoundDeps maven enforce plugin now, because Spark 3.0.0
requires a lower version of jackson (2.10.0) while other libraries,
including CQL driver, require a higher version of jackson.
2. Support null value mutation semantics to comply with TinkerPop 3.5.0.
property(single, prop, null) removes the property while
property(list/set, prop, null) is simply ignored.
3. Introduce a workaround for traversal strategies which can be removed
once TINKERPOP-2568 is fixed.
4. Upgrade apache common configuration to configuration2 to comply
with the same TinkerPop breaking change. Now users won't experience the
problem reported at #1447 anymore, since configuration2 by default does
not read comma delimited string as a list of values.
5. Other minor changes mostly caused by breaking changes in TinkerPop.

Closes #2611, #2624, #1447

Signed-off-by: Boxuan Li <liboxuan@connect.hku.hk>
possible_reason:
4.
Upgrade apache common configuration to configuration2 to comply
with the same TinkerPop breaking change.

commit_message:
Many changes to bring closer to support of spring-social 1.1.4

Merge changes from Alfresco/spring-social-salesforce
-Unable to fully use Salesforce Sandbox
--Remove hardcoded userinfo url in useroperations
--Add the ability to pass in the gateway url for the authorization
server used in userinfo
-getBlob is returning a closed InputStream
--override ByteArrayHttpMessageConverter to allow all media types
--change extractor to use the byteArray message converter in the
RestRemplate
--to keep the existing method signature as InputStream return byteArray
as byteArrayInputStream
--remove default content-type header used in other tests to allow return
on non json content.
-Update Salesforce API version used
--Add method to set version to be used by method calls
--Add validation to version provided
--Default version is now v37.0
--Refactor where version and default version are located (ApiTemplate
and ApiOperations
--Update all uses of API_VERSION to now use getVersion method
--Update and Add Tests for version string
--Add getServices method that does not require version to be passed but
uses the current set version
--When the version number passed to setVersion is invalid (format,
blank, null) we no longer silently fail but throw
InvalidSalesforceApiVersionException.
-JsonParseException when response is BAD_OAUTH_TOKEN
--Bad_OAuth_Token is returned as a single string not json as expected
from other errors
--Add code to look at jsonParseException to test if it is actually this
error. Return this error in the proper format to be handled as a known
error. This will allow so that when (if) Salesforce fixes this issue a
new release will not be needed.
--Response handling suffers drom the same end of stream close issue
after single use.  Buffer the stream as a byteArray so that it can be
used in error handling and additional testing after an exception is
thrown.
--When Bad_OAuth_Token is found it is returned as
InvalidAuthorizationException instead of as an
InsufficientPermissionException.  The former should be recoverable with
a token refresh (uses a refresh token).  The latter should indicate a
need to reauthenticate and possible approve additional
permissions/scopes for the user.

Update/remove dependencies to those required for 1.1.4
Refactor any errors or changes based on dependency changes
Update author and license header copyright year

on non json content.

-Update Salesforce API version used

commit_message:
Update to OSGi 5 and Jetty 8 (#703).

Several 3rd-party components are updated.
Now we have a Jetty 8, that means Servlet API 3.0
And now we have Felix 4.4, that means OSGi 5

The details:

Felix HTTP Jetty 2.2.0 -> 2.3.0
    Jetty 7.6.13 -> Jetty 8.1.14
        Servlet API 2.5 -> Servlet API 3.0

Pax Runner 1.7.5 -> 1.8.6
    Felix 3.2.2 -> Felix 4.4.1
        OSGi 4.2 -> OSGi 5

Felix Configuration Admin 1.2.8 -> 1.8.0
Felix EventAdmin 1.2.12 -> 1.4.0

See #703.

- Framework logging changed from commons-logging to SLF4J

- Libraries versions updated :
    blazeds =>4.0.0.14931
    spring => 3.0.5.RELEASE

    log4j => 1.2.16

- Due to the migration to BlazeDS 4, you must comment the following section 
in startup/flex/config/src/main/resources/services-config.xml :

        <login-command class="flex.messaging.security.TomcatLoginCommand" server="Tomcat"/>

- Due to the migration to BlazeDS 4, you must delete the following section 
in webapp/pom.xml :
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.adobe.blazeds</groupId>
      <artifactId>blazeds-opt</artifactId>
    </dependency>

- servlet-api dependency was transitively added to tha webapp due to a bad dependency declaration in one
of the used libraries. This is in violation of the servlet specification and resulted in a warning during the
application startup. We have now excluded this bad servlet-api dependency, but it has to be declared now in the
webapp pom.xml as "provided". So add the following dependency section in webapp/pom.xml :
    <dependency>
      <groupId>javax.servlet</groupId>
      <artifactId>servlet-api</artifactId>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>

commit_message:
Totally get rid of Jersey and the JAX-RS API

Now we solely rely on Spring to provide the web application part
of the project.

This avoids the mix between Spring controllers and JAX-RS classes
which makes understanding the project a bit more complex.

This commit also introduces the following changes:

* Remove dependencies related to MongoDB ; Spring can't properly handle
  a JDBC connection with the noise that the Mongo related dependencies
  produce.

  The MongoDB stuff is broken at the moment anyway.

* Remove all the XML related configuration. There are more or less
  cryptic and detached from the code which lessen the change to
  understand what's going on behind the scene when there's an issue.

  Let's rely on annotations instead.

* Avoid having dozen different files to configure properties and
  specifically the connection to the database.

  Everything is now stored in `application.properties`.

* Properly package the logging stuff with the application. Otherwise,
  debugging is painful and we need to download external JARs and put
  them in a folder in the classpath.

Modernize the pom.xml:
* Update jmxutils to 1.12

osgi: fix dependencies

We were importing both OSGI interfaces relocated by Felix and the ones
provided by the org.osgi groupId.

This was causing conflicts at runtime on certain deployments. We now only
use the Felix ones.

Signed-off-by: Pierre-Alexandre Meyer <pierre@mouraf.org>
possible_reason: osgi: fix dependencies

commit_message:
util: switch to Ehcache 3 jars

The integration mostly relies on the JCache (aka JSR-107) specification,
except for Shiro which is Ehcache specific.

Main user-facing changes:

* cache metrics are now prefixed with jcache.statistics
  instead of net.sf.ehcache.Cache
* new ehcache.xml syntax (see http://www.ehcache.org/documentation/3.3/xml.html)

See https://github.com/killbill/killbill/issues/587.

Signed-off-by: Pierre-Alexandre Meyer <pierre@mouraf.org>
possible_reason: util: switch to Ehcache 3 jars

Change JSON parsers to use jackson-databind

- add package parser.json
- introduce classes that represent our JSON files
- change global, month and holiday parsers accordingly
- remove org.json (mainly JSONObject)
- pass strings before parsing (f.e. in Main)

benefits:
- reliable library for json parsing (jackson is widely used)
- validation and helpful error messages
- explicit definition of json structures
- parsers act as interface between json classes and our data classes
- no changes to our data model

commit_message:
[JENKINS-37062] incorporate changes from stapler servlet 3.1

Downstream updates from stapler/stapler#131

The stapler API was built using servlet 2.5 and yet Jenkins uses 3.1.
This meant some of the code that stapler used was missing new methods
that where part of the updated spec and if a plugin happened to call
them you would end up with a LinkageError or some other crazyness.

This also make Jenkins depend on a dummy version of the old serlet-api
maven co-ordinates such that if any plugin gets aa dependency on it
transitivly (e.g. Jenkins test harness) they will get a version with no
code so the classpath should always be clean (this was more an issue for
eclipse than an mvn command)
possible_reason: [JENKINS-37062] incorporate changes from stapler servlet 3.1

commit_message:
Major refresh of Hush to HBase 1.0.0.

- This patch updates the SchemaManager to support the new HTD and HCD features, drops unneeded internal classes. 
- Table names are now stored as TableName instances rather than byte[]. HTablePool was removed in favour of the new Connection.getTable() plus subsequent table.close(). 
- All HTable were switched to Table, same for HBaseAdmin to Admin.
- All flushCommits() calls were removed since they were removed. 
- Jetty and all dependencies (JSP being a big one) were updated to the latest version, which required some minor code updates in Hush itself. The biggest issue was the POM and getting the transitive dependencies as explicit one right. 
- Fixed also two NPE problems that caused problems in userstats.jsp (stats were null) and getting the username without cookies (in HushUtils).
- The schema.xml was cut down to what is needed, the list of new features is too long to add to the XML.
possible_reason: Major refresh of Hush to HBase 1.0.0.

Cleanup logging dependencies

removed the global test dependency on slf4j-nop, because it clutters the
dependency information and is in many cases just wrong (e.g. the build-tools
module has no such dependency).

As a consequence, the maven tests now log error messages about missing slf4j
implementations again. For now however, this seems to be the best solution,
since none of the LearnLib modules actually require a logging implementation
as it is merely a dependency for the end-user, who will use LearnLib.

The best example is the 'examples' module, for which a logback runtime
dependency was added.

commit_message:
MH-12831, Fixing dependencies

This patch is part of getting Opencast getting to not fail with Java 9+.
It fixes a lot of dependency problems I've found when making the
necessary changes for Java 9+ (e.g. explicitly adding java.ee dependencies).

Note that despite the large number of changes the only two non-test,
non-dependency fixes are two places in our code where `commons.lang` was
still used instead of `commons.lang3`.

The main parts of this patch are:

- Explicitly declaring the java.ee dependencies:
  https://stackoverflow.com/a/43574427/2352895
- Fixing obvious dependency problems which popped up due to some modules
  dependencies now being declared more precisely.
- Updating and centralizing the version of `rest-assured` which was
  partly specified incorrectly.

Note that while this patch fixes a lot of the Java 9 problems and nearly
all modules can now be built using Java 9, a few (unfortunately large)
problems still persist:

- The default date format for some languages has changed in Java 9 which
  causes a few tests in the admin interface to fail. I expect this to be
  harmless and think the tests just need adjustment, but I did not want
  to make that change without the ability to test it properly.
- We are on ElasticSearch version 1.7.6. Java 9 is supported starting
  with version 6.2. We had already discussed in the past that upgrading
  this is something we would like to do. Unfortunately, it's a lot of
  work.
- We also need to upgrade to Karaf 4.2.x. At the moment, the assembly
  steps fail due to us using an old Karaf version. Fortunately, we are
  already on 4.0.10 which isn't that far away (compared to ES). Still,
  it's some work.

Hence, consider this a first step. Obviously, I could also not test for
any runtime problems so far. The other problems need to be resolved
first.

Note though, that this does not only fix dependencies for Java 9. Most
of the problems are quite relevant for older Java versions as well.
possible_reason:
Note that despite the large number of changes the only two non-test,
non-dependency fixes are two places in our code where `commons.lang` was
still used instead of `commons.lang3`.

commit_message:
MH-13254, Automate Dependency Checking

This patch enables *optional* automated dependency checks on Opencast
modules. While Opencast rpovides a default configuration, modules still
need to opt-in by including the maven-depenency-plugin.

If this works, long term, we could at some point enforce dependency
checking globally to prevent depedency problems right from the start.

---

Note that the dependency plugin is not perfect and may complain about
pure runtime dependencies (e.g. it does not know that we may want to
attach a logger to our test and may complain about it being an
unnecessary dependency).

But the plugin allows making exceptions for such cases. This means that
developers can still declare any dependencies they like, but they are
forced to consider if they actually make sense since they need to
possibly whitelist them if they are not directly used.

---

This patch provides some example usages, including some whitelistings in
the implementation classes.

commit_message:
Externalize & update Elasticsearch

This patch upgrades to the Elasticsearch High Level REST Client 7.4
which needs an Elasticsearch 7 node to work with.
Since embedding Elasticsearch is no longer supported, the embedded node
is removed. Elasticsearch 7 does no longer allow to store different
document types in the same index. Instead, one index per document type
is required. So the code was changed to create four "sub indices", one
for each document type. This means, that for the admin UI index, there
are actually 4 Elasticsearch indices now. The same applies for the
external API index.

So from now on, running an external Elasticsearch node is mandatory in
order to be able to run Opencast.

One small test case was removed as it would now require a running
external Elasticsearch node during execution time.
possible_reason:
This patch upgrades to the Elasticsearch High Level REST Client 7.4
which needs an Elasticsearch 7 node to work with.
Externalize & update Elasticsearch

commit_message:
Make Opencast compatible with JDK11

This patch improves compatibility with newer JDKs. Namely, it is now
possible to build and run Opencast with JDK11. For JDK12 and JDK13,
building Opencast is possible as well, while running Opencast is not
possible with these JDKs, yet.

Since we want to stay compatible with JDK1.8 for now, language features
of newer JDKs cannot be used at the moment. Once we decide to drop
JDK1.8 support, new language features can be used without any further
preparations, except increasing the `jdk.version` in the main POM.

The following table shows the current state of Opencast compatibility
with some JDKs.

| JDK  | Build | Run | Language Features |
|------|-------|-----|-------------------|
|JDK1.8|  YES  | YES |        YES        |
|JDK11 |  YES  | YES |        NO         |
|JDK13 |  YES  | NO  |        NO         |

Compatibility with JDK 9, 10, and 12 was not tested, but for JDK 9 and
10, full (build _and_ runtime) compatibility is much likely given.

To also achieve runtime compatibility with JDK12 and JDK13, Karaf 4.3
is needed, which is not yet released. Once the new Karaf version is
available, enabling JDK12 and JDK13 runtime compatibility should be
fairly easy.

In order to achieve runtime compatibility with JDK11, a little quirk was
necessary: `jakarta.xml.bind-api-2.3.3.jar` had to be packaged with
Opencast as this version is required for JDK11. Version 2.3.3 of this
library is already released, but not yet uploaded to Maven Central
because it is part of the upcoming Java EE release, which was not yet
published. Once this is published, the packaged jar can most likely be
replaced with a Maven reference. Once Karaf comes with a Java EE version
including version 2.3.3 of jakarta.xml.bind-api or higher, it should no
longer be necessary to manually manage this dependency at all.

To enable compatibility with newer Java versions, lots of dependencies
were updated. Also, Java EE is currently in the process of renaming all
artifacts named `javax.something` to `jakarta.something-else` due to
legal issues with the term `javax`. Hence, a lot of pom files had to be
touched as upgrading a dependency also meant to rename it in many cases.

After upgrading all the dependencies, a few issues came up which are
worth being mentioned:

- JPA was complaining about duplicate column names in some queries. So I
  had to extend 3 `@JoinColumn` annotations.
- With Java 9, breaking changes to locales were made which caused some
  date formatting code parts to break. This was fixed by setting the
  JDK's `java.locale.providers` property to `COMPAT`.
- The `Lazy` class caused strange behavior where class files of classes
  using `Lazy` were compiled differently by different JDKs, even though
  both JDKs were compiling for the same byte version. This caused test
  failures. Since `Lazy` could be easily replaced and seemed to not
  provide any advantages, it was removed.
- Since Jetty had to be updated from version 1.x to version 2.x, some
  major changes to the `rest-test-environment` bundle were necessary.

The file `system.properties.append` used to configure XML processing
related factories to use internal JDK classes. This was changed to use
JDK-independent classes to improve compatibility with future JDKs.

Upgrading the ActiveMQ client library was not necessary, but was done
anyway.

Since a lot of dependencies were changed, the Maven part of `NOTICES`
was re-generated.
possible_reason: longer be necessary to manually manage this dependency at all.

2016-06-23 Implemented a demo UI for Mars Net using html5/js/css and included a few other demo. 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
I. NEW
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Added IndexController.java, Greeting.java, GreetingController.java. 
a. run SpringAppLeaf.java.
b. open a browser and enter "localhost:8080" to show a Mars Net demo (jquery and bootstrap powered)
c. enter "localhost:8080/greeting" to demo GET annd POST capability
d. enter "localhost:8080/hello" to demo local links
e. enter "localhost:8080/main" to see a modern html5 personal site (jquery and skel powered)
f. enter "localhost:8080/backstory" for seeing the backstory page

Ref 1: https://github.com/Qkyrie/spring-thymeleaf-example
Ref 2: https://github.com/almasaeed2010/AdminLTE
 

3. Added /static folder in mars-sim-ui inside src/main/resources for holding css/images/js.

4. Added the following html pages to be stored in /templates folder in mars-sim-ui inside src/main/resources. :
a. greeting.html and result.html are for testing GET and POST
b. starter.html is for Mars Net demo
c. hello.html and hello2.html are for demonstrating simple links
d. main.html if for demonstrating setting up a modern html5 personal site.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

commit_message:
Replace json-simple by own JSON serializer #89

Replace json-simple by own JSON writer and perform UTF-8 encoding within the JSON writer.

Motivation: json-simple produces a notable amount of garbage during JSON serialization. The default interchange format is String that concatenates data using StringBuilder.

The own implementation uses a facade to write bytes on an underlying stream. This reduces the garbage so data is not necessarily duplicated during serialization.

commit_message:
Upgrade Jersey server

Major version upgrade from 1.19.3 to 2.27. New version has a different
groupId and package name. Licenses are different too because Jersey
code moved to Eclipse Foundation. It uses newer version of the JAX-RS
specification which contains many new interfaces.

Majority of code changes are around container dependency injection.
Jersey 1.x had its own dependency injection framework and 2.x uses
HK2 as the dependency injection container. Registration of custom
injectables is thus very different. They are now registered in
`ComponentsBinder` which is itself registered in the top-level
container component called `ResourceConfig`.

Other notable change is in transaction handling for REST requests.
Previously, transactions were open in a request dispatcher. There is
no such concept in new Jersey. Container request filter is used
instead.

Removed usages of proprietary Jersey APIs like base64 decoding.
Removed dependency on the old custom forked JAX-RS API.
possible_reason:
There is
no such concept in new Jersey.
Container request filter is used

commit_message:
Fix dependency issues with hamcrest

Motivation:

We use 3 (!) libraries to build mock objects - easymock, mockito, jmock.
Mockito and jMock pulls in the different versions of Hamcrest, and it
conflicts with the version pulled by jUnit.

Modifications:

- Replace mockito-all with mockito-core to avoid pulling in outdated
  jUnit and Hamcrest
- Exclude junit-dep when pulling in jmock-junit4, because it pulls an
  outdated Hamcrest version
- Pull in the hamcrest-library version used by jUnit explicitly

Result:

No more dependency hell that results in NoSuchMethodError during the
tests
possible_reason: We use 3 (!) libraries to build mock objects - easymock, mockito, jmock.

commit_message:
Update to Java EE 7

Updating to the Java EE 7 versions:  Servlet 3.1, JSF 2.2, EL 3.0, and
CDI 1.2.  Compile against Java SE 8.

Side effects:

1.  Update to Tomcat 8.5.  Repaired so that it works.
2.  Update Showcases to latest version.
3.  Update Weld to 2.4.7 and Mojarra to 2.3.7.
4.  Update JSTL to 1.2 and use jstl group.
5.  Paramaterize so that versions stay consistent.
6.  Update existing versions to latest.
7.  Remove special version of Xalan that was needed for Java EE 6.
8.  Exclude jconsole so the JDK version is used instead of the Wildfly
version.
9.  Update to latest httpclient 4.5.6

Caveats:

1.  Tests fail locally in integration-gwt, transform-minify, and
rewrite-impl-servlet-tests.  Some tests fail that contain IgnoreFor
notation, suggesting that the test is fragile.  One test checks if
content is uppercased.  I'm not sure why that is a requirement there.
possible_reason:
Update to Java EE 7
Updating to the Java EE 7 versions:  Servlet 3.1, JSF 2.2, EL 3.0, and
CDI 1.2.

commit_message:
Switch from Unirest to Apache HTTP Client and add Timeout option.

In the previous version, requests longer than 1 minute
would simply die, ignoring Rundeck's job timeout. Additionally, since
Rundeck only applies it's own timeout after a step has finished
executing, added a timeout option to this plugin so timeouts
can better be controlled.

commit_message:
Switch to using gson for JSON serialization

This patch changes JSON provider to GSON, skipping jackson
packaging completely.  GSON is used by many upstream ODL
projects and is the desired single JSON library for the
future.

Some unit tests surrounding Handlers needed to be ignored
temporarily due to classpath issues;  some of the overlapping
technology is tested in integration-test so the AAA team
feels it is okay to temporarily disable for now.

For now, this change exposes a provider package for the
GsonProvider so that other projects running into the same
issue can utilize it without copying and pasting code.
Later, it will be moved somewhere more intelligent.

Change-Id: I6033980d0fdaa31be32e2e77a0b9f869a755246b
Signed-off-by: Robert Varga <robert.varga@pantheon.tech>
Signed-off-by: Ryan Goulding <ryandgoulding@gmail.com>
possible_reason: Switch to using gson for JSON serialization

commit_message:
Do not pull in JSR305 by default

The migration to findbugs:annotations is actively hurtful to us,
as JSR305 is clashing on javax.annotation package with JEE
annotations.

This patch removes findbugs:annotations, making them a banned
dependency, and instead defines spotbugs:annotations and
findbugs:jsr305.

spotbugs:annotations replaces findbugs:annotations as the default
dependency.

JIRA: ODLPARENT-198
Change-Id: I3e113fb3af3f2cdd6e4cd6b22ffc0dcac5efbcf9
Signed-off-by: Robert Varga <robert.varga@pantheon.tech>
possible_reason:
The migration to findbugs:annotations is actively hurtful to us,
as JSR305 is clashing on javax.annotation package with JEE

commit_message:
Convert yang-xpath-impl into a JPMS module

This is a bit more involved, as we are using a different
javax.inject and do not use osgi.cmpn but
org.osgi.service.component.annotations directly.

The latter results in a dependency on an automatic module, but
that is not really a problem as we never touch them at runtime.

Since we do not want to export out implementation directly, and
it still needs to be discoverable via reflection, we dedicate
org.opendaylight.yang.xpath.impl.di package for that purpose.
It will come in handy for other injection frameworks as well.

JIRA: YANGTOOLS-1145
Change-Id: Ie80b02eba551fa89c334f20484e386d808316ca3
Signed-off-by: Robert Varga <robert.varga@pantheon.tech>
possible_reason:
This is a bit more involved, as we are using a different
javax.inject and do not use osgi.cmpn but
org.osgi.service.component.annotations directly.

commit_message:
HTML-751 - Increase minimum version to 2.1.0 and enable testing support of all 2.x versions (#203)

HTML-751 - Compatibility and test coverage for all 2.x lines of OpenMRS

* Create 4.x branch and update artifact version to 4.0.0-SNAPSHOT

* Remove support for Logic Expressions in htmlformentry.

* Remove support for the <standardRegimen> tag, due to removal of core support in 2.x

* Update minimum version of OpenMRS to 2.1.0, adjusting unit tests, compatibility classes that are no longer needed, and other API updates.  OpenMRS 2.1.0 chosen over 2.0.0 due to problems in 2.0.0 surrounding saving Obs Groups within encounters.  Testing profiles added that support testing against 2.1, 2.2, 2.3, 2.4.

* Adding in exit from care method based on what was in core 1.12 and removed in 2.x, in order to support existing exitFromCare tag compatibility.  Move transaction annotations from htmlformentryservice interface and onto implementation.

* Fix tests for new condition data in 2.3, accounting for 2.3 data model changes, by modifying the 2.1 dataset xml, and then adding only changes in a new xml file.

* Improve WorkflowStateTagTest to make the tests a little clearer to read and implement, re-add test case that had been removed in previous commit, make END STATE non-terminal in order to avoid conflicting logic in how core handles terminal states across releases.

* HTML-745: Allow condition tag to be preset with a concept.
Co-authored-by: Dimitri R <dimitri@mekomsolutions.com>
possible_reason:
* Update minimum version of OpenMRS to 2.1.0, adjusting unit tests, compatibility classes that are no longer needed, and other API updates.
OpenMRS 2.1.0 chosen over 2.0.0 due to problems in 2.0.0 surrounding saving Obs Groups within encounters.

commit_message:
engine: Upgrade to JUnit Jupiter

This patch upgrades the oVirt Engine to use the modern JUnit Jupiter
5.2 for its unit tests. JUnit Jupiter is quite different from the old
JUnit 4 and even JUnit 5 vintage, so this patch contains quite a few
changes:

1. Maven:
   a. The org.junit.vintage:junit-vintage-engine was removed and
      replaced with org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter-engine in order
      to provide the basic JUnit JUpiter capabilities.
   b. The org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter-params dependency was added
      in order to provide the @ParameterizedTest annotation and its
      related helpers. See 7a and 7b for additional details.
   c. The org.mockito:mockito-junit-jupiter dependency was added in
      order to provide MockitoExtension. See 7c for additional
      details.
   d. org.junit.platform:junit-platform-surefire-provider was added
      as an explicit dependency to the maven-surefire-plugin in order
      to properly execute JUnit Jupiter tests.

2. Lifecycle annotations:
   a. org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeAll and
      org.junit.jupiter.api.AfterAll are used as drop-in replacements
      for org.junit.BeforeClass and org.junit.AfterClass,
      respectively.
   b. org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeEach and
      org.junit.juiter.api.AfterEach are used as replacements for
      org.junit.Before and org.junit.After, respectively. One slight
      difference is that the vintage engine treats methods overriding
      methods annotated with @Before/@After as if they themselves were
      annotated with that annotation. JUnit Jupiter requires that
      overriding methods be explicitly annotated with
      @BeforeEach/AfterEach themselves.

3. Test annotations:
   a. org.junit.jupiter.api.Test was used as a drop-in replacement
      for org.junit.Test in the simple case of an annotation with no
      arguments, which org.junit.jupiter.api.Test doesn't support.
   b. Usages of org.junit.Test with the "expected" arguments were
      replaced with org.junit.jupiter.api.Test and an explicit call
      to org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions#assertThrows on the
      relevant code. A side benefit of this approach is that it makes
      the test a tad stricter, and prevents false-positives where the
      "preparation" code throws the exception instead of the actual
      code the test intended to test.
   c. Usages of org.junit.Test with the "timeout" arguments were
      replaced with org.junit.jupiter.api.Test and an explicit call
      to org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions#assertTimeout on the
      relevant code. A side benefit of this approach is that it makes
      the test a tad stricter, and prevents false-positives where the
      "preparation" code takes too long and not the actual code the
       test intended to test.
    d. org.junit.jupiter.api.Disabled was used as a drop-in
       replacement for org.junit.Ignore.

4. Assertions:
   a. The variants of the assertion methods in org.junit.Assert that
      do not include a failure message (assertTrue, assertFalse,
      assertEquals, assertNotEquals, assertArrayEquals, assertNull,
      assertNotNull, assertSame, assertNotSame)
      were replaced by the drop in replacements in
      org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.
   b. The variants of the methods mentioned in 4a that are overloaded
      to include a failure message as the first argument were
      replaced with their counterparts in
      org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions, but these variants have the
      failure message as the *last* argument, not the *first*
      argument.
   c. assertEquals(double expected, double actual, double delta) and
      its overloaded counterpart with a message do not accept deltas
      of 0.0 like the methods in org.junit.Assert used to. 0.0001 is
      used as an arbitrary small delta to signify both values are
      equal in the project's regards.
   d. org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions does not contain an assertThat
      method. Instead, as per the recommendation in the documentation,
      Hamcrest's org.hamcrest.MatcherAssert#assertThat was used
      instead.

5. Assumptions
   a. The variants of the assumeTrue and assumeFalse methods in
      org.junit.Assume that do not include a failure message were
      replaced by the drop in replacements in
      org.junit.jupiter.api.Assumptions.
   b. The variants of the methods mentioned in 5a that are overloaded
      to include a failure message as the first argument were
      replaced with their counterparts in
      org.junit.jupiter.api.Assumptions, but these variants have the
      failure message as the *last* argument, not the *first*
      argument.
   c. org.junit.jupiter.api.Assumptions does not contain assumeNull
      and assumeNotNull methods. Instead, the same behavior was
      achieved by using assumeTrue and assumeFalse with explicit
      conditions.

6. @Rules and @ClassRules
   a. ExpectedException usages were replaced with explicit calls to
      assertThrows. Similarly to the usecase of org.junit.Test with
      an "expected" parameter, explicitly using assertThrows on the
      call(s) that are supposed to throw an exception allow for finer
      grained control and slightly stricter tests.
   b. TemporaryFolder was replaced, in the one place it was used,
      ConfigurationTest, with inline @BeforeEach and @AfterEach
      methods that implemented the limited subset of functionality
      that test required.
   c. MockConfigRule was removed, as JUnit Jupiter no longer
      supports rules, and was replaced with MockConfigExtension.
      This extension is configured by implementing a
      mockConfiguration() public static method that returns a
      Stream<MockConfigDescriptor> to be mocked. While extensions do
      not provide the flexibility of changing the mocked
      configuration in runtime, like the old MockConfigRule did, it
      allows configuring, per method, what mock configuration
      supplier method will be used (by annotating it with the
      @MockedConfig method), which seems to be sufficient to the
      project's needs.
   d. MockEngineLocalConfigRule was removed, as JUnit Jupiter no
      longer supports rules, and was replaced with
      MockEngineLocalConfigExtension.
      This extension is configured by implementing a
      mockEngineLocalConfiguration() public static method that
      returns a Stream<Pair<String, String>>> to be mocked.
   e. InjectorRule was removed, as JUnit Jupiter no longer supports
      rules, as was replaced with InjectorExtension. Instead of the
      boiler-plate code required to bind mocks, this extension will
      automatically detect public fields annotated with @InjectedMock
      and will bind them to the type they are declared by.
   f. ExecutorServiceRule was removed, as JUnit Jupiter no longer
      supports rules, as was replaced with ExecutorServiceExtension.
   g. RandomUtilsSeedingRule was removed, as JUnit Jupiter no longer
      supports rules, as was replaced with
      RandomUtilsSeedingExtension.
   h. UiCommonSetupRule was removed, as JUnit Jupiter no longer
      supports rules, as was replaced with UiCommonSetupExtension.
      The pointless inner interface, Mocks, was removed, and instead
      users can access the mocks via the traditional getters (e.g.,
      Frontend.getInstance()). Additionally, RETURN_DEEP_STUBS was
      used when mocking the ConstatnsManager instead of boiler-plate
      implementing the same logic.

7. Runners
   a. org.junit.runners.Parameterized, which no longer exists (since
      JUnit Jupiter does not have a concept of runners any more) was
      replaced with explicit annotations of
      org.junit.jupiter.params.ParameterizedTest on the relevant
      tests. Usually the old @Parameters were replaced with a
      @MethodSource, but in the places were other source could be used
      easily, they were.
   b. org.junit.experimental.theories.Theories, which no longer
      exists (since JUnit Jupiter does not have a concept of runners
      any more) was replaced with explicit annotations of
      org.junit.jupiter.params.ParameterizedTest on the relevant
      tests. Usually the old @DataPoint and @DataPoints were replaced
      with a @MethodSource, but in the places were other source could
      be used easily, they were.
   c. org.mockito.junit.MockitoJunitRunner,
      org.mockito.junit.MockitoJunitRunner.Strict,
      org.mockito.junit.MockitoJunitRunner.Silent and the deprecated
      org.mockito.junit.runners.MockitoJunitRunner were replaced with
      a @ExtendWith(MockitoAnnotation.class) annotation. Where it
      worked effortlessly the default strict form of the extension
      was used, but in most cases,
      @MockitoSettings(strictness = Strictness.LENIENT) was added.
      Removing this leniency is a possible task for future patches.
   d. SpringJUnit4ClassRunner was replaced with SpringExtension.

8. Specific changes
   a. GetConfigurationValueQueryTest was cleaned up to have a single
      @ParameterizedTest cover all the permutation instead of four
      boiler-plate @Test methods.
   b. Since @ParameterizedTest does not allow extending classes to
      supply their own @MethodSource, AppErrorsTest and
      VdsmErrorsTest were removed, and the logic of both the tests
      was condensed in to AbstractConstantsWithLookupTestCase which
      was renamed to the concrete ConstantsWithLookupTest.
   c. BackendEntityAssignedPermissionsResourceTest was made abstract
      so that junit does attempt to run its test cases (and fail since
      it doesn't have a no-arg constructor).

Change-Id: I3d9b4a4f9461ef7cdacf24399743d0d6b1a98a2a
Signed-off-by: Allon Mureinik <amureini@redhat.com>
possible_reason:

commit_message:
Client changes for RUN_LOCALLY=true, Server changes for launching
nodes/hubs, introduce Selion-Common, refactoring, and misc updates or fixes

Client Changes
-------------------
- Made Selenium-Server and Selion-Grid dependencies optional in SeLion
  "client" - They are only required for local runs
- Removed iso-driver config values which do not apply to iso-driver 0.6.5
- Removed AbstractNode
- Introduced AbstractBaseLocalServerComponent which provides
  base implmentations for all LocalServerComponents
- Removed LocalGridConfigFileParser and test -- class no longer required
- Removed localnode.json from client's src/main/resources
- Changed LocalGridManager, LocalNode, LocalIOSNode, and LocalHub,
  and LocalSelendroidNode to use SeLion-Grid for their needs
- Nodes are now started on probed ports vs. fixed ports
- Chromedriver, phantoms, etc downloaded and used for local runs, when
  missing
- Remove Hub.java hack
- Upgrade TestNG, appium-client, and snakeyaml dependencies
- Added guarding against ClassNotFound exception when SeLion-Grid
  and/or selenium-server is/are not available when running locally via
  SeLion client

Server Changes
----------------------
- Refactoring and introduction of new launcher/spawner classes in SeLion-Grid
	- Added IOSDriverJarSpawner
	- Added SelendroidJarSpawner
	- Added AppiumSpawner
	- Added ThreadedLauncher for launching selenium hub and web nodes
	  in the same process on a different Thread
	- Added shutdown() to SeLionGridLauncher
	- Introduced interface RunnableLauncher
	- Added abstract and base classes for RunnableLaunchers which are
	  a) in the same process, b) in a separate process, and c) mobile, in a
	  separate process
	- Introduced option to disable continuos restart for the RunnableLauncers
	  which are process spawners
	- Introduced enumeration InstanceType which is used to track the current
	  instance SeLion-Grid is managing and/or booting (e.g. hub, node, etc)
- Added JVM shutdown hook for launcher/runners which spawn a new
  process -- This should help cleanup on Windows
- Relocated class ArtifactDetails and reduced visibility.. it is only used by the
  FileDownloader
- Moved several classes from depending org.apache.commons.lang3 (a
  transitive  dependency of selenium-server -- may not be in the class path) to
  org.apache.commons.lang (which is available)
- Updates to ConfigParser -- fixed LOGGER.entering and added ability to
  getJsonObject
- Added ability for download.json to specify artifact "roles" -- which when
  considered by  FileDownloader will only result in an artifact download
  (or "checksum" verification) if the  artifact in question is required for the
  current InstanceType
- SeLionConfg.json now allows the user to define default args for Appium,
  Selendroid, and ios-driver
- Introduced MinimalIOSCapabilityMatcher in "server"
- Add Default-Suite.xml for SeLion-Grid
- FileDownloader can now skip last modified check on file AND
  can be told to not cleanup downloads which may have happened
  previously in the same JVM process
- FileDownloader can now process by artifact names

Other Misc Changes
----------------------------
- Addressed some Javadoc issues from misc classes
- Enabled Dependency Convergence
- Fix #103 -- Usage of org.json
- Add some test classes
- Downgrade to ios-driver 0.6.5 everywhere -- many of our tests and
  sample code still require ios-driver 0.6.6-SNAPSHOT. 0.6.6-SNAPSHPOT
  can be re-intoruced by updating the SelionConfig.json for SeLion-Grid
  and through an pom.xml update on the user's end.
- Introduction of SeLion-Common - Started to push classes which were
  duplicate or needed by more than one SeLion component into this new artifact
- Relocated and/or renamed some classes which were pushed to common
- Moved some SeLionGridConstant vars into common in new class
  SeLionConstants -- they are needed for both client and server and
  since client can run w/o server (it's an optional dependency), it made
  sense to do this.
- Updated archetype to include SeLion-Grid and selenium-server dependencies
possible_reason:
- Introduction of SeLion-Common - Started to push classes which were
duplicate or needed by more than one SeLion component into this new artifact
- Relocated and/or renamed some classes which were pushed to common

password.

NOTE:
To run web console only in testing environment I use different web.xml in each

commit_message:
Remove octarine-bson depepency on mongo-java-driver uber-jar

The mongo-java-driver and mongodb-driver “uber-jars” are no longer published. Applications that reference either of these artifacts must switch to either mongodb-driver-sync or mongodb-driver-legacy, depending on which API is being used. Care should be taken to ensure that neither of the uber-jars are included via a transitive dependency, as that could introduce versioning conflicts.

Right now because of above, any application using octarine-bson cannot move to mongo 4.x driver because octarine-bson is pulling in the old mongo-java-driver 3.x uber-jar and causing a versioning conflict.
In reality, octarine-bson only needs org.mongodb.bson so change it to only depend on that, and avoid the versioning conflict.
possible_reason: Right now because of above, any application using octarine-bson cannot move to mongo 4.x driver because octarine-bson is pulling in the old mongo-java-driver 3.x uber-jar and causing a versioning conflict.

commit_message:
Use slf4j and logback for logging.

Since quartz requires slf4j, we'll use it as our logging abstraction
everywhere instead of jboss-logging. And, since we want logging to work
out-of-the-box, we need a logging implementation. We were bringing in
log4j, but have switched to logback since it requires less dependencies
to work as an slf4j implementation, and it is the successor to log4j.

Known issues:

* If a user wants to use a different logging provider, they'll need to
  exclude logback and bring in their own. If they don't exclude, it may
  still work, but they'll get a stern message from slf4j about multiple
  implementations.

* The messaging tests now throw "java.lang.ClassNotFoundException:
  org.jboss.logmanager.LogManager", but this doesn't affect the tests,
  nor does it show up for consumers of wunderboss-messaging. I don't
  currently know the cause of this message.
possible_reason: Use slf4j and logback for logging.

commit_message:
Replace commons-cli with JCommander

This commit breaks backwards compatibility of the CLI by introducing commands instead of some options, and removing values for others.

The operating mode is now specified as a command ("single", "many"). Captcha delay is now configured through a property, and so is dry run balance.
possible_reason: Replace commons-cli with JCommander

commit_message:
Compile and test RoboZonky on JDK 9 as well (#146)

Another step towards #113. Has a lot of refactoring in order to keep decent mutation coverage. There is still a lot of smaller problems with Java 9, such as runtime warnings etc., most of which will only ever be fixed by moving to proper modularity.

My thought is to reify the metadata schema, then transform DDL into
predicates which do the DML on the metadata schema, then perform the
corresponding H2 DDL commands

Implementation of DDL transactions (rather than single statement DDL
transactions) would be through Calcite "caching", implicitly making the
trade offs of expensive ops (build index, drop column, drop table,
schema, etc).

Any DDL in batches would be simulated through Calcite, and DML mixed
into all that would operate against this simulation.  The implicit trade
off is one cannot do massive bulk ops through loops or whatever, unless
teh ops are state replicable without breaking bandwidth.

Extracting GOCTransport (renamed to GusTransport) and EndpointInfo classes from the GOCNotifier class, so it can be used by the GusNotifier class.
Migrating GusNotifier class to use GusTransport for auth and getting token. Removing duplicate code.
Updating GusTransport class to use a LoadingCache to hold the current EndpointInfo and manage refreshes. Also refactored the logic to get token into a Supplier. Making it so that HttpClient is re-used instead of being one-time-use.
Re-using GusTransport instance in GusNotifier and GOCNotifier instead of being one-time use. Also adding in retries for GusNotifier and GOCNotifier if notification fails to post. If failure is due to bad token, the notifier will attempt to refresh the token cache.
Adding metrics to track number of retries and number of failures for GOCNotifier and GusNotifier.

commit_message:
Switch from TestNG to JUnit

All other SciJava projects use JUnit.

TestNG has a lot of cool features. However, the TestNG Eclipse plugin
(at least historically, in my experience) causes problems when installed
side-by-side with the JUnit Eclipse plugin: every time you run a unit
test, Eclipse annoying asks whether to use JUnit or TestNG. It is much
simpler to just keep everything in JUnit, which is good enough for the
vast majority of testing needs.

commit_message:
Updating the http client and support API exception

The API returns errors with an HTTP code 400, 404 or 500 depending on
the cause with a json object that contains the failure reason.  The
error message should be populate to the JMX calling client, translated
to the appropriate exception.

This patch adds the ability to detect API failure and throw a runtime
exception with the returned message.

It is up to the calling method what to do with the exception, if it
would do nothing, the calling client would get a RuntimeException,
depends on origin MBean definition, the caller can catch the exception
and throw a specific kind.

Note that any exception that is thrown must be known to the JMX client
or it will not be able to process it.

As a first step, this patch replaces the jersey client to the newer
version under glassfish, which has an easy way of getting a Reply
object, and check its status before returning the results.

The only difference in the method that uses the APIClient is the use of
MultivaluedHashMap.

The following MBean implementation where changed

ColumnFamily
CompactionManager
Gossiper
EndpointSnitchInfo
CacheService
StorageProxy
StorageService

Signed-off-by: Amnon Heiman <amnon@scylladb.com>

commit_message:
Upgrade to version 1.8.0

The main issues included in this release are:

General:

  1. Now Sentilo is compliant with Redis 4, MongoDB 4, Tomcat 8.5  and JRE 1.8

    Sentilo has been tested with the above versions of Redis, MongoDB, Tomcat
    and JRE and from today these are the recommended versions. Previous
    versions are also supported but without any guarantee. We strongly
    recommend to upgrade to these latest versions as soon as possible.

  2. Add support to federate different Sentilo instances.

PubSub Server / API REST:

  3. New field ttl in sensor metadata which allows you to define a custom ttl
     for each sensor.

    In previous releases, sensor data expired time (a.k.a. ttl) was defined
    globally as a configuration parameter and it was always the same for all
    sensors.

  4. New parameter socket.tcp.backlog which allows to adapt your server request
     throughput

    Sentilo uses this parameter to invoke the listen method of the server socket.
    As the JDK documentation defines, this parameter "[...] sets the maximum queue
    length for incoming connection indications (a request to connect) to the count
    argument. If a connection indication arrives when the queue is full, the
    connection is refused"

  5. Add more info about sensors to the response of the /catalog service API

    The information about sensors returned by the /catalog service now include
    fields like sensor's state.

Catalog:

  6. Improvements in user password definition

    We have redesigned how user passwords are defined: by default, when a new
    user is created its password is equal to its id. Additionally we have add
    a new page which allows any user to change its password at any moment
    (whether or not him will be an administrator). This new password must follow
    a password policy which ensures the use of strong passwords.

  7. New control of maximum number of failed login attempts.

    When authentication attempts exceed the number of permitted consecutive failed
    attempts (configuration parameter with a default value of 3), the user will be
    in a locked state until an administrator enabled him.

  8. Enhancements at the Universal viewer to make it more responsive.

    We have completely redesign how data is displayed when user inspects the content
    of a component, improving its responsiveness and its usability.

  9. New sensor data types and support to visualize media data types

    If sensor data type is defined as one of the new data types available (FILE_LINK,
    VIDEO_LINK, IMAGE_LINK or AUDIO_LINK), i.e. sensor data contains links to external
    resources, then when sensor data will be represented the Catalog will try to use
    an appropriate media player to visualize it into the Catalog.

  10. New administrator option that displays a list with all active subscriptions

  11. Improve visualization of sensor data when it contains a JSON message.

  12. Add CSRF and XSS protection.

Agents:

  13. New Sentilo Kafka Agent

  14. Sentilo activity-monitor agent now supports Elasticsearch 5 and 6

  15. Fix bugs related to the use of the historian agent in a multitenant environment.
possible_reason:
4.
New parameter socket.tcp.backlog which allows to adapt your server request
throughput

    In previous releases, sensor data expired time (a.k.a. ttl) was defined
    globally as a configuration parameter and it was always the same for all
    sensors.

  4. New parameter socket.tcp.backlog which allows to adapt your server request
     throughput

    Sentilo uses this parameter to invoke the listen method of the server socket.
    As the JDK documentation defines, this parameter "[...] sets the maximum queue
    length for incoming connection indications (a request to connect) to the count
    argument. If a connection indication arrives when the queue is full, the
    connection is refused"

  5. Add more info about sensors to the response of the /catalog service API

    The information about sensors returned by the /catalog service now include
    fields like sensor's state.

Catalog:

  6. Improvements in user password definition

    We have redesigned how user passwords are defined: by default, when a new
    user is created its password is equal to its id. Additionally we have add
    a new page which allows any user to change its password at any moment
    (whether or not him will be an administrator). This new password must follow
    a password policy which ensures the use of strong passwords.

  7. New control of maximum number of failed login attempts.

    When authentication attempts exceed the number of permitted consecutive failed
    attempts (configuration parameter with a default value of 3), the user will be
    in a locked state until an administrator enabled him.

  8. Enhancements at the Universal viewer to make it more responsive.

    We have completely redesign how data is displayed when user inspects the content
    of a component, improving its responsiveness and its usability.

  9. New sensor data types and support to visualize media data types

    If sensor data type is defined as one of the new data types available (FILE_LINK,
    VIDEO_LINK, IMAGE_LINK or AUDIO_LINK), i.e. sensor data contains links to external
    resources, then when sensor data will be represented the Catalog will try to use
    an appropriate media player to visualize it into the Catalog.

  10. New administrator option that displays a list with all active subscriptions

  11. Improve visualization of sensor data when it contains a JSON message.

  12. Add CSRF and XSS protection.

Agents:

  13. New Sentilo Kafka Agent

  14. Sentilo activity-monitor agent now supports Elasticsearch 5 and 6

  15. Fix bugs related to the use of the historian agent in a multitenant environment.

commit_message:
With the update of some of the dependencies and the removal of some of very old
dependencies, some codes have been refactored:
- The application cache in the Caching Engine is now based upon the new version
  of ehcache. In its new version the element expiry mechanism has now to be
  explicitly defined. If ehcache 3 provides a default mechanism for TTL-based
  expiry or TTI-based expiry, nothing is provided to define a mechanism based
  upon both TTL and TTI as it was in ehcache 2. So a custom expiry mechanism
  is defined to implement close the way the TTL-and-TTI-based expiry was
  managed in ehcache 2.
  With the new version of ehcache, any null key throws immediately
  NullPointerException. This cause problems with MessageManager that uses the
  application cache and particularely in tests. So, the tests were updated to
  initialize MessageManager and a check is performed in MessageManager when
  accessing the application cache to catch the NullPointerException exception.

- In the last version of Apache POI, the attributes are now encapsultated by
  getter. So replace all the direct attribute accesses by their counterpart
  getter.

- The iCal4J API as some subtle changes. The HTMLProperty is modified
  consequently to those changes.

- In the new Jackson version, the null fields are now also serialized.
  Set a configuration parameter to the ObjectMapper in JSONCodec so that
  Jackson behaves like its previous versions.

- The very old informa library to produce or to consume RSS feeds is now
  replaced by the last version of Rome. All the codes that used informa are now
  refactored to use Rome instead of informa.

- Spring social connectors are updated to their last stable version. For doing,
  as LinkedIn has migrated their OAuth mechanism to OAuth2 and discourages
  strongly the use of OAuth1, the Linked connector in Silverpeas is updated to
  use OAuth2 instead of OAuth1.
possible_reason:

commit_message:
Updated to use jackson to read yaml into beans, rather than using a custom deserializer

Years ago, the original thought was to make the file "user friendly" by not exposing the direct structure of the underlying object there, and instead using "friendly" names for the fields. Since then, I've changed my mind. I think that the typical user of this will be very technical and not at all put off by camelCase field names, and the reduced code means it will be much more maintainable, as there's not much interesting going on (the exception being the way the default values are handled, but even that is not complicated; see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/65483376/deserialize-yaml-in-java-using-defaults-read-earlier-in-file/).

commit_message:
[all] switch to Dagger 2 for dependency injection and IDEA for primary development

The existing LifeCycle feature that heavily relied on Guice has been reworked
into the `com.spotify.heroic.lifecycle` package.

LifeCycle has to be explicitly exported through the appropriate subsystem.

Using `metric` as an example, it expects modules to export
MetricModule.Out#life() to govern the lifecycle of any encapsulated components.

Finally, due to annotation processing issues with Eclipse
(see [./eclipse](eclipse)), a feature Dagger 2 heavily relies on, it is now
recommended to use IDEA for development.
Because of this, all code has been reformatted using the provided style in
idea/code-style.xml.

Details:

* Re-organize HeroicCore to better handle external lifecycles.
* Constructor-based `@Inject` everywhere.
* Removed all guice dependencies.
possible_reason: [all] switch to Dagger 2 for dependency injection and IDEA for primary development

commit_message:
Migrate from Liquibase to Flyway, from HSQL to H2

This change replaces Liquibase[1] with Flyway[2] for database schema
migrations for the following reasons:

1. To avoid DB lock contention issues at startup

We dealt with a number of production outages due to the fact that
Liquibase caused (or otherwise contributed to) lock contention issues
at startup (i.e. when Liquibase needs to lock tables in order to apply
changes to the DB) that resulted in DB connection pool starvation. This
behavior was never isolated and repeated in a test environment, but was
observed several times in practice in production. The workaround has been
to reduce the instance count in production from 4 to 1, but this has its
own negative effects (no redundancy in the case of an app crashing).

So this move to Flyway is in some ways an experiment in which we will
see over time whether it too can result in these locking / starvation
issues. Testing the application under load in an 8-instance environment
suggests that it will not, but only sustained time in production will
tell for sure.

2. Flyway's plain-SQL approach is clearer and more suitable to our needs

Liquibase has a powerful DSL that acts as an abstraction layer over SQL,
making it simple to develop in memory against HSQL while deploying to
production against Postgres. However, it comes at the cost of needing
to understand that DSL (which in practice means looking things up in
Liquibase's documentation each time a change needs to be made). This is
a minor hassle for project committers, but is more important when
considering this application's purpose as a reference app; plain SQL is
immediately clear to a larger percentage of the audience than
Liquibase's DSL would be, therefore Flyway's approach is preferred.

3. Flyway is (or appears to be) faster than Liquibase at startup time

Liquibase initialization took approximately 3 seconds on an MBP against
an in-memory DB. Flyway initialization takes less than 1 second. This is
significant given that it takes overall startup time from ~12 seconds to
~8 seconds, i.e. more efficient when in a tight loop of code changes and
restarts. Note that this comparison isn't perfectly apples-to-apples, as
the Liquibase arrongement had 3 changesets whereas there is now just one
consolidated changeset under Flyway.

This commit also migrates from HSQL to H2 as the in-memory database used
for development and automated testing. The primary reason is because H2
offers an explicit "PostgreSQL compatibility mode", making it feasible
to configure Flyway with a unified set of SQL files, as opposed to
maintaining two copies, one for the in-memory DB and one for the
production DB. HSQL does not have this option. This change was quite
straightforward to perform - H2 was effectively a drop-in replacement,
and side-by-side comparisons of executing the test suites demonstrates
little or no difference with regard to performance.

[Finishes #57709992]
[1]: http://www.liquibase.org
[2]: http://flywaydb.org
possible_reason:
This commit also migrates from HSQL to H2 as the in-memory database used
for development and automated testing.

DATAJPA-207 - Fixed query creation for projections on native queries.

When executing a projecting query through a native query we must not use em.createNativeQuery(String, Class<?>) as this expects an entity type as type parameter. commit_message:
SEC-2542: Use exclusions to remove duplicate dependencies

A number of projects had duplicate dependencies on their classpaths
as a result of the same classes being available in more than one
artifact, each with different Maven coordinates. Typically this only
affected the tests, but meant that the actual classes that were
loaded was somewhat unpredictable and had the potential to vary
between an IDE and the command line depending on the order in which
the aritfacts appeared on the classpath. This commit adds a number of
exclusions to remove such duplicates.

In addition to the new exclusions, notable other changes are:

 - Spring Data JPA has been updated to 1.4.1. This brings its
   transitive dependency upon spring-data-commons into line with
   Spring LDAP's and prevents both spring-data-commons-core and
   spring-data-commons from being on the classpath
 - All Servlet API dependencies have been updated to use the official
   artifact with all transitive dependencies on unofficial servlet API
   artifacts being excluded.
 - In places, groovy has been replaced with groovy-all. This removes
   some duplicates caused by groovy's transitive dependencies.
 - JUnit has been updated to 4.11 which brings its transitive Hamcrest
   dependency into line with other components.

There appears to be a bug in Gradle which means that some exclusions
applied to an artifact do not work reliably. To work around this
problem it has been necessary to apply some exclusions at the
configuration level

Conflicts:
	samples/messages-jc/pom.xml
possible_reason:
- All Servlet API dependencies have been updated to use the official
artifact with all transitive dependencies on unofficial servlet API
artifacts being excluded.

commit_message:
SEC-2542: Use exclusions to remove duplicate dependencies

A number of projects had duplicate dependencies on their classpaths
as a result of the same classes being available in more than one
artifact, each with different Maven coordinates. Typically this only
affected the tests, but meant that the actual classes that were
loaded was somewhat unpredictable and had the potential to vary
between an IDE and the command line depending on the order in which
the aritfacts appeared on the classpath. This commit adds a number of
exclusions to remove such duplicates.

In addition to the new exclusions, notable other changes are:

 - Spring Data JPA has been updated to 1.4.1. This brings its
   transitive dependency upon spring-data-commons into line with
   Spring LDAP's and prevents both spring-data-commons-core and
   spring-data-commons from being on the classpath
 - All Servlet API dependencies have been updated to use the official
   artifact with all transitive dependencies on unofficial servlet API
   artifacts being excluded.
 - In places, groovy has been replaced with groovy-all. This removes
   some duplicates caused by groovy's transitive dependencies.
 - JUnit has been updated to 4.11 which brings its transitive Hamcrest
   dependency into line with other components.

There appears to be a bug in Gradle which means that some exclusions
applied to an artifact do not work reliably. To work around this
problem it has been necessary to apply some exclusions at the
configuration level

Conflicts:
	samples/messages-jc/pom.xml
possible_reason:
- All Servlet API dependencies have been updated to use the official
artifact with all transitive dependencies on unofficial servlet API
artifacts being excluded.

Initial change to SLF4J was because of what turned out to be unrelated
errors in the Shadow plugin.  SLF4J is a wrapper that allows many
different logging frameworks to be used, and that level of flexibility
is probably not needed for Shadow.  Log4j 2 works fine and is a
stand-alone logging solution.

commit_message:
SWARM-1440: Separate build profiles further (#576)

* SWARM-1440: Separate build profiles further

Motivation
----------
Reduce what's built when `swarm.product.build` is set and remove testsuites from reactor for it.

Modify dependencyManagement so that testsuite modules don't have WF dependencies included to make testsuites "cleaner" in terms of dependencies.

Modifications
-------------
Added `build-parent` to be the parent of all artifacts we build as part of WF Swarm so that it can include any dependencies, such as feature packs, that are purely required for building.

Moved `maven-enforcer-pattern-size` into root of project.

Tweaked the build profiles so that depenendencyManagement contains appropriate WF Swarm artifacts that are then made available to testsuite modules for us. Also added some common dependencies into /testsuite so that all tests can use them.

Result
------
Doesn't impact the functioning of the product, mostly impacts what's built with `-Dswarm.product.build`.

* Remove commented out dependency
possible_reason:
-------------
Added `build-parent` to be the parent of all artifacts we build as part of WF Swarm so that it can include any dependencies, such as feature packs, that are purely required for building.

commit_message:
THORN-2229 AbstractMethodError when building using Maven 3.6.0

Motivation
----------

Thorntail projects fail to build with Maven 3.6.0.

Modifications
-------------

Dependecies on org.eclipse.aether:aether-*:1.1.0 were replaced by org.apache.maven.resolver:maven-resolver-*:1.3.1. Class RepositorySystemSessionWrapper implements missing method getFileTransformerManager().

Result
------

Build works with Maven 3.6.0, 3.5.2 and 3.3.9.
possible_reason:
THORN-2229 AbstractMethodError when building using Maven 3.6.0
Dependecies on org.eclipse.aether:aether-*:1.1.0 were replaced by org.apache.maven.resolver:maven-resolver-*:1.3.1.
Class RepositorySystemSessionWrapper implements missing method getFileTransformerManager().

commit_message:
Java 13 compiler _runtime_ compatibility

This means that we're still compiling to Java 8, but the compiler itself
may be Java 13. This also means that the runtime during testing is Java
13.

A few adjustments needed to be made:
- Jacoco only supports Java 13 from v 0.8.5 upward
- Findbugs was updated to Spotbugs, which still needed a bump of asm lib
to v7.2. The _next_ release will depend on asm 7.2. There were still two
findings which we needed to ignore.
- Log4j1.2 has no support for the new java version strings and then
drops support for MDS because it thinks that we're running Java 1 :) We
updated to log4j2 for tests.
possible_reason:
drops support for MDS because it thinks that we're running Java 1 :) We
updated to log4j2 for tests.

commit_message:
Full Mavenization - Part 1

Maven runs
1) mvn clean install
2) mvn site with profile 'checks' to get code coverage

* Removing ant build scripts.
* Removing thirdParty/_lib, _report, org.apache.ivy from git ignore
* Removed all ivy files
* Updated some versions throughout
* Fixed glitches with hamcrest used by mockito all
* Added tomcat8 plugin
* Moved items in waffle-filter demo to be consistent with maven layout
* No longer excluding module builds after resolving issues
* Removed libraries from classpath as maven controls this
* Added sonar nature for further code verifications
* jetty build sticks javadocs as no public classes causes failure
* added some more site pages instances
* added readme.txt in third party
* added missing settings items (note these will ultimately go away once
clearly over to maven)
possible_reason:
* Updated some versions throughout
* Fixed glitches with hamcrest used by mockito all
* Added tomcat8 plugin

commit_message:
Make WikibaseRepository type safe

Parse responses from Wikibase to Java objects to make them type safe. This
makes the client code less error prone, contains the JSON parser dependency
to the WikibaseRepository class and makes refactoring those classes easier.

This replaces json-simple with Jackson, which is already a dependency in
the project.

Still to check:

At this point, an invalid change will put the whole batch of changes in
error. This could happen if a field is invalid (non parseable date in a
date field, invalid integer in an integer field, ...). I'm not sure if
that's an error that is sufficiently frequent to need specific handling.

Change-Id: Ibd2a2e217931333dafa894dd003f3fdbf6c2157e
possible_reason:
This replaces json-simple with Jackson, which is already a dependency in
the project.
